To fix a broken focus outline without disrupting the layout, use `outline-offset` to create space around the outline and ensure it doesn't overlap other elements. Example:
css
button:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid #005fcc;
  outline-offset: 2px;
}

This approach respects accessibility while preserving the visual design. Avoid removing outlines entirely or using `outline: none` without providing an alternative focus indicator.

Scroll-driven animations in CSS allow animations to progress based on the scroll position of a container, rather than time. This is achieved using the `@scroll-timeline` rule. Example:
css
@keyframes fade-in {
  from { opacity: 0; }
  to { opacity: 1; }
}

.element {
  animation: fade-in linear;
  animation-timeline: scroll();
}

This animates the element's opacity as the user scrolls past it. Scroll-driven animations are useful for parallax effects, reveal animations, and other scroll-based interactions.
